---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="GNSS Error Sources">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals">Fundamentals</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Error Sources</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Fundamentals · Article 3 of 5</span>
        <h1>Error Sources</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          A standalone GNSS receiver claims 3–5 metre accuracy but delivers 15 metres. A survey receiver
          claims centimetre accuracy but drifts to decimetres under tree cover. Every deviation from
          truth has a cause. This article explains each error source — what causes it, how large it is,
          and how differential and dual-frequency techniques mitigate it.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>14 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#overview">Error budget overview</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ionosphere">Ionospheric delay</a></li>
          <li><a href="#troposphere">Tropospheric delay</a></li>
          <li><a href="#multipath">Multipath</a></li>
          <li><a href="#clock">Clock errors</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ephemeris">Ephemeris errors</a></li>
          <li><a href="#receiver-noise">Receiver noise</a></li>
          <li><a href="#differential">How differential GNSS reduces errors</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="overview">Error budget overview</h2>
      <p>
        GNSS positioning errors come from four categories of source: the <strong>space segment</strong>
        (satellite clock and orbit errors), the <strong>propagation path</strong> (ionosphere and troposphere),
        the <strong>local environment</strong> (multipath and interference), and the <strong>receiver itself</strong>
        (measurement noise and hardware biases).
      </p>
      <p>
        The combined effect is captured in the <strong>User Equivalent Range Error (UERE)</strong> — the
        total ranging error seen by the receiver on a single satellite. The final positioning error
        depends on UERE multiplied by DOP (see the <a href="/learn/fundamentals/dilution-of-precision">DOP article</a>):
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">σ_position = DOP × σ_UERE</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          A PDOP of 2.0 with UERE of 3 m gives a 3D position error of ~6 m (1σ).
          Reducing either factor improves positioning accuracy.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Error budget table -->
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Error source</th>
              <th>Typical range (1σ)</th>
              <th>Mitigated by</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Ionospheric delay</strong></td>
              <td>1 – 10 m (single-freq)</td>
              <td>Dual-frequency, differential, model</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Tropospheric delay</strong></td>
              <td>0.2 – 2 m</td>
              <td>Models (Saastamoinen, VMF)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Multipath</strong></td>
              <td>0.1 – 10 m (code), ~1 cm (phase)</td>
              <td>Antenna, choke ring, BOC signals</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Satellite clock</strong></td>
              <td>~1 m (broadcast), ~3 cm (precise)</td>
              <td>Broadcast corrections, IGS products</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Ephemeris error</strong></td>
              <td>~1 m (broadcast), ~3 cm (precise)</td>
              <td>Broadcast corrections, IGS products</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Receiver noise</strong></td>
              <td>0.1 – 0.5 m (code), ~1 mm (phase)</td>
              <td>Smoothing, averaging, quality hardware</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="ionosphere">Ionospheric delay</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>ionosphere</strong> is a layer of the atmosphere between approximately 50 km and
        1,000 km altitude where solar radiation ionises gas molecules, creating free electrons. These
        free electrons slow the group velocity of GNSS signals (increasing the apparent pseudorange)
        while advancing the carrier phase — a peculiarity of dispersive media.
      </p>
      <p>
        The ionospheric delay on pseudorange is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">I = 40.3 × TEC / f²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where TEC is Total Electron Content in TECU (1 TECU = 10¹⁶ electrons/m²) and f is frequency in Hz.
          At L1 (1575.42 MHz), 1 TECU of TEC causes ~0.016 m of delay.
          Typical TEC ranges from 1–10 TECU at night to 10–100 TECU during solar maximum at equatorial latitudes.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="error-magnitude">
        <div class="magnitude-bar">
          <div class="magnitude-label">Ionospheric delay on L1</div>
          <div class="magnitude-scale">
            <div class="magnitude-fill" style="width:80%; background: rgba(255,71,87,0.7);">
              <span>1 – 100 m (vertical)</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="magnitude-note">Worst case: equatorial regions at solar maximum. Typical mid-latitude daytime: 5–15 m.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Key characteristics</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Frequency-dependent:</strong> Delay is proportional to 1/f² — this enables dual-frequency receivers to eliminate it entirely using the ionosphere-free combination.</li>
        <li><strong>Elevation-dependent:</strong> Signals at low elevation angles pass through more ionosphere. The <em>mapping function</em> relates vertical TEC to slant delay: I_slant = I_vertical / cos(z), where z is the zenith angle at the ionospheric pierce point.</li>
        <li><strong>Spatially correlated:</strong> Nearby receivers see nearly identical ionospheric delays — the basis of differential GNSS. Correlation degrades beyond ~1,000 km baseline length.</li>
        <li><strong>Time-varying:</strong> Follows a diurnal cycle (peak at 14:00 local time), seasonal cycle and 11-year solar cycle. During geomagnetic storms, delay can become highly irregular (scintillation).</li>
        <li><strong>Worst at equatorial latitudes:</strong> Plasma bubbles forming after local sunset cause rapid, unpredictable fluctuations — ionospheric scintillation. See the <a href="/dashboards/environment">GNSS Environment Watch</a>.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Mitigation strategies</h3>
      <div class="mitigation-grid">
        <div class="mitigation-card">
          <div class="mit-title">Dual-frequency</div>
          <div class="mit-desc">Form the ionosphere-free combination from two frequencies. Eliminates ~99.9% of first-order ionospheric delay. Requires dual-frequency capable receiver.</div>
          <div class="mit-effectiveness effectiveness-high">Effectiveness: High</div>
        </div>
        <div class="mitigation-card">
          <div class="mit-title">Differential GNSS</div>
          <div class="mit-desc">Use corrections from a nearby reference station. Effective up to ~100 km baseline for code; ~50 km for carrier phase RTK.</div>
          <div class="mit-effectiveness effectiveness-high">Effectiveness: High</div>
        </div>
        <div class="mitigation-card">
          <div class="mit-title">Klobuchar model</div>
          <div class="mit-desc">GPS broadcasts 8 ionospheric model coefficients. Corrects ~50% of the RMS ionospheric delay. Available to all single-frequency receivers at no cost.</div>
          <div class="mit-effectiveness effectiveness-med">Effectiveness: Moderate</div>
        </div>
        <div class="mitigation-card">
          <div class="mit-title">NeQuick (Galileo)</div>
          <div class="mit-desc">Galileo broadcasts NeQuick model parameters (3 coefficients). Provides better correction than Klobuchar particularly at low latitudes.</div>
          <div class="mit-effectiveness effectiveness-med">Effectiveness: Moderate</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="troposphere">Tropospheric delay</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>troposphere</strong> (0–50 km altitude) slows GNSS signals regardless of frequency —
        unlike the ionosphere, it is a non-dispersive medium, so dual-frequency receivers cannot eliminate it.
        The delay has two components:
      </p>

      <div class="component-grid">
        <div class="component-card">
          <div class="comp-name">Dry (hydrostatic) component</div>
          <div class="comp-value">~2.3 m at zenith</div>
          <div class="comp-desc">
            Caused by dry atmospheric gases — primarily nitrogen and oxygen. Highly stable and well-modelled.
            Accounts for ~90% of total tropospheric delay. Can be accurately predicted from surface pressure
            measurement alone.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="component-card">
          <div class="comp-name">Wet component</div>
          <div class="comp-value">0.01 – 0.35 m at zenith</div>
          <div class="comp-desc">
            Caused by water vapour. Highly variable in space and time — the dominant source of tropospheric
            modelling error. Accurately predicting it requires water vapour measurements (radiosondes,
            GNSS-derived precipitable water vapour).
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The total zenith tropospheric delay (ZTD) is typically 2.0–2.6 m, increasing with elevation
        as the mapping function sin(elevation) applies:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">T_slant = ZTD / sin(elevation)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          At 10° elevation, a 2.3 m zenith delay becomes ~13 m of slant delay.
          This is why low-elevation satellites are often down-weighted or masked (elevation mask angle
          of 10–15° is typical).
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🌦️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>GNSS meteorology:</strong> The wet tropospheric delay is proportional to the
          integrated water vapour along the signal path. By measuring the delay precisely (using PPP
          or network RTK), researchers can recover precipitable water vapour content — a valuable
          input to weather forecasting models. GNSS is now a standard tool in meteorology.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="multipath">Multipath</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Multipath</strong> occurs when GNSS signals reach the receiver antenna via more than one
        path — the direct line-of-sight signal plus one or more reflected signals off buildings,
        terrain, vehicles or other surfaces.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reflected signal arrives slightly later than the direct signal (because it travels a longer
        path) and with reduced amplitude (energy is lost at reflection). When the reflected signal
        combines with the direct signal at the antenna, it distorts the correlation peak used to measure
        the pseudorange.
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρ_measured = ρ_true + Δρ_multipath</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Code multipath error Δρ_multipath is bounded by half the chip length: max ≈ 146 m for C/A code,
          but typical urban values are 1–10 m. Carrier phase multipath is bounded by half the wavelength:
          max ≈ 9.5 cm for L1.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Multipath diagram -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">Direct and reflected signal paths</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 220" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr3" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M2 1L8 5L2 9" fill="none" stroke="context-stroke" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- Satellite -->
          <circle cx="120" cy="40" r="10" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="120" y="26" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)">Satellite</text>
          <!-- Antenna/Receiver -->
          <rect x="300" y="160" width="40" height="30" rx="4" fill="none" stroke="var(--text2)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="320" y="175" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--sans)">Rx</text>
          <!-- Building -->
          <rect x="480" y="90" width="80" height="100" rx="4" fill="none" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4 2"/>
          <text x="520" y="145" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Building</text>
          <!-- Direct path -->
          <line x1="128" y1="46" x2="305" y2="160" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr3)"/>
          <text x="200" y="95" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)">Direct</text>
          <!-- Reflected path -->
          <line x1="128" y1="46" x2="480" y2="120" stroke="#ff4757" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#arr3)"/>
          <line x1="480" y1="120" x2="340" y2="160" stroke="#ff4757" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#arr3)"/>
          <text x="380" y="112" font-size="11" fill="#ff4757" font-family="var(--sans)">Reflected (longer path)</text>
          <!-- Extra path length indicator -->
          <text x="320" y="205" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Reflected path longer → later arrival → pseudorange error</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <h3>Multipath characteristics</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Environment-dependent:</strong> Severe in urban canyons, near water, on aircraft carriers and in open-pit mines. Negligible in open-sky environments.</li>
        <li><strong>Elevation-dependent:</strong> Low-elevation satellites experience more multipath because signals arrive at grazing angles more likely to reflect. Elevation masks help.</li>
        <li><strong>Slowly time-varying:</strong> As the satellite moves, the multipath geometry changes, causing slow oscillations in the pseudorange error. Multipath cannot be removed by carrier smoothing of code.</li>
        <li><strong>Not spatially correlated:</strong> Unlike ionospheric delay, multipath is unique to each receiver location and antenna environment. It cannot be differenced away in RTK.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Mitigation strategies</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Antenna design:</strong> Choke ring antennas suppress ground-reflected signals. Right-hand circular polarisation (RHCP) antennas reject left-hand polarised reflections (reflected signals change polarisation).</li>
        <li><strong>Signal processing:</strong> Narrow correlator, double-delta correlator, multipath mitigation technology (MMT) — all reduce code multipath by sharpening the correlation peak.</li>
        <li><strong>BOC modulation:</strong> Binary Offset Carrier signals (Galileo E1, GPS L1C) have a sharper correlation peak than BPSK, reducing code multipath susceptibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Site selection:</strong> In survey applications, avoiding reflective surfaces within 5–10 m of the antenna is the most effective mitigation.</li>
        <li><strong>Carrier phase smoothing:</strong> Code pseudoranges can be smoothed using the more precise carrier phase observations (Hatch filter), reducing code noise but not multipath.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="clock">Clock errors</h2>
      <p>
        GNSS positioning depends critically on time. A clock error of 1 nanosecond translates to
        approximately <strong>30 cm of ranging error</strong> (c × 1 ns = 0.3 m).
      </p>

      <h3>Satellite clock errors</h3>
      <p>
        Each GPS satellite carries multiple atomic clocks — rubidium and caesium oscillators with
        stability of 10⁻¹³ to 10⁻¹⁴ over one day. Despite this precision, they drift slightly from
        GPS system time. The control segment monitors this drift and broadcasts clock correction
        parameters (a₀, a₁, a₂) in the navigation message:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">δt_sv = a₀ + a₁(t − t_oc) + a₂(t − t_oc)²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where a₀ = clock bias (seconds), a₁ = frequency drift (s/s), a₂ = frequency drift rate (s/s²),
          and t_oc is the reference epoch. After applying this correction, residual satellite clock errors
          are typically &lt;1 m equivalent range. Precise clock products from IGS reduce this to ~3 cm.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Receiver clock errors</h3>
      <p>
        Consumer and survey receivers use quartz oscillators — cheap, small and power-efficient, but
        with stability 10⁵–10⁶ times worse than atomic clocks. The receiver clock offset δt_r is
        therefore an unknown that must be estimated simultaneously with position (the fourth unknown
        in the navigation solution).
      </p>
      <p>
        Because δt_r appears identically in all pseudoranges, it cancels in <strong>single-difference</strong>
        observations between two satellites (same receiver, different satellites). This is exploited
        in RTK processing to remove the common-mode receiver clock error.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="ephemeris">Ephemeris errors</h2>
      <p>
        Trilateration requires knowing the exact position of each satellite. The satellite's position
        is computed from <strong>ephemeris</strong> parameters broadcast in the navigation message —
        a set of Keplerian orbital elements plus perturbation corrections updated every 2 hours.
      </p>
      <p>
        Broadcast ephemeris accuracy is typically 0.5–2 m in the radial direction (along the
        line of sight) and somewhat worse in the along-track and cross-track directions. Errors
        in the radial direction map directly into ranging error; along-track errors are attenuated
        by the geometry.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🛰️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Precise ephemeris:</strong> The International GNSS Service (IGS) produces precise
          orbit and clock products computed from a global network of reference stations.
          IGS final products (available 12–18 days after the fact) have orbit accuracy of ~2.5 cm
          and clock accuracy of ~75 ps (~2 cm equivalent). Ultra-rapid products are available
          in near-real-time with ~5 cm orbit accuracy — essential for PPP.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="receiver-noise">Receiver noise</h2>
      <p>
        Even with perfect signals and no environmental effects, the receiver's measurement process
        introduces noise. This comes from thermal noise in the RF front-end and analogue-to-digital
        conversion, plus quantisation noise from the correlation process.
      </p>
      <p>
        Code measurement noise is typically 0.1–0.5 m (1σ) for quality receivers, proportional to
        the inverse of the signal-to-noise ratio. Carrier phase noise is much lower — typically
        0.5–2 mm (1σ) — which is why phase measurements are preferred for precision positioning.
      </p>
      <p>
        Receiver noise is <strong>white</strong> (uncorrelated in time) and averages down with
        integration. This is why stationary receivers improve accuracy over time through position
        averaging, and why carrier smoothing of code (Hatch filter) works — the smooth, quiet
        phase is used to remove the noisier code variations.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="differential">How differential GNSS reduces errors</h2>
      <p>
        The key insight of differential GNSS is that most errors are <strong>spatially correlated</strong>
        — a reference station nearby experiences almost identical ionospheric delay, tropospheric delay,
        satellite clock error and ephemeris error as the rover. By computing corrections at the
        reference station (where the true position is known) and applying them to the rover, these
        correlated errors largely cancel.
      </p>

      <!-- Error budget comparison diagram -->
      <div class="budget-compare">
        <div class="budget-col">
          <div class="budget-title">Standalone GNSS</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 60px; background: rgba(255,71,87,0.3);">Ionosphere ~5 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 30px; background: rgba(240,165,0,0.3);">Troposphere ~1 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 20px; background: rgba(251,191,36,0.3);">Sat clock ~1 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 20px; background: rgba(0,153,255,0.3);">Ephemeris ~1 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 20px; background: rgba(0,212,170,0.3);">Multipath ~2 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 10px; background: rgba(163,230,53,0.3);">Noise ~0.3 m</div>
          <div class="budget-total">Total UERE ~10 m</div>
        </div>
        <div class="budget-col">
          <div class="budget-title">Differential GNSS (&lt;100 km)</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 8px; background: rgba(255,71,87,0.3);">Residual iono ~0.3 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 8px; background: rgba(240,165,0,0.3);">Residual tropo ~0.2 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 4px; background: rgba(251,191,36,0.3);">Sat clock &lt;0.1 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 4px; background: rgba(0,153,255,0.3);">Ephemeris &lt;0.1 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 20px; background: rgba(0,212,170,0.3);">Multipath ~2 m</div>
          <div class="budget-item" style="height: 10px; background: rgba(163,230,53,0.3);">Noise ~0.3 m</div>
          <div class="budget-total">Total UERE ~2 m</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Notice that multipath and receiver noise are <em>not</em> reduced by differential techniques —
        they are local effects unique to each receiver. This is why even with a perfect RTK system
        and short baseline, multipath remains the dominant error source in difficult environments.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Ionosphere</div>
          <div class="summary-body">1–100 m. Frequency-dependent. Eliminated by dual-frequency; significantly reduced by differential GNSS within 100 km.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌦️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Troposphere</div>
          <div class="summary-body">0.2–2 m. Frequency-independent. Modelled (Saastamoinen, VMF3). Wet component is the hard part — requires water vapour data to model well.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🏙️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Multipath</div>
          <div class="summary-body">0.1–10 m (code), &lt;10 cm (phase). Local — not differenced away. Mitigated by antenna design, choke ring, site selection and signal processing.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⏱️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Clock and ephemeris</div>
          <div class="summary-body">~1 m broadcast. ~3 cm precise (IGS). Satellite clock error cancels in single-difference observations. Receiver clock error is the fourth unknown.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals/signals-and-frequencies" class="nav-prev">← GNSS Signals and Frequencies</a>
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals/coordinate-systems" class="nav-next">Coordinate Systems →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House. Chapters 5, 6, 7.</li>
          <li>Misra, P. & Enge, P. (2011). <em>Global Positioning System: Signals, Measurements and Performance</em>, 2nd ed. Ganga-Jamuna Press. Chapter 4.</li>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. & Montenbruck, O. (eds.) (2017). <em>Springer Handbook of Global Navigation Satellite Systems</em>. Springer. Chapters 19–22.</li>
          <li>Saastamoinen, J. (1972). Atmospheric correction for the troposphere and stratosphere in radio ranging of satellites. <em>Geophysical Monograph</em>, 15, 247–251.</li>
          <li>IGS Products. <a href="https://igs.org/products/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">igs.org/products →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

